              </a>
             </td>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
            </tr>
           </tbody>
          </table>
         </figure>
        </div>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         With Indocybin, scientists and psychologists began doing real research on psychedelics\xe2\x80\x99 potential benefits. According to the
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUMtuxCAM_Jrl1ghI2CUHDr30NyIeToKWQASmUf6-bHKoZMljj8Yjj9UIS8qn2lNBUgvkyTvFnlz2YhiJU4NjUkjiyzRngE37oDBXIHs1wVuNPsVLQSkXZFVSMGl7I9zryUQvZmmYGAewz9kBE4KTj8-kq_MQLSj4hXymCCSoFXEvj_77wX9aHcfRGbDvAOecanSXUZfy0rhiL_EHVVNQN1y-NsA1udKWe_Eh2dP42AbiFaecMkZH1gvZ8451IublyJoZB4-Bbgvv7jv23dm0kaxiQpOyj0uj36veIFxEe3lqfavR4zlB1CaAu9PAO7_rOTx3UBGOEgAR8r38RCTpyPnrRZqbSy3J-G_0By5hh2s" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          Beckley Foundation
         </a>
         , the number of scientific studies published on psilocybin grew from five in 1958 to forty in 1968. The American Psychologists Association focused on LSD research, specifically a paper titled
         <em>
          <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUMmOwyAM_Zpya2QgCzlw6GV-I2JxUtQEInCmyt8PbQ4jWbL1nqy3OEO4pHzqPRViR8E8Ba95L5Ts2pF53XquOsVCmeaMuJmwasoHsv2wa3CGQorfDwDRsadWIFGNspfWcul7L3Ac_AzSub41wszsozOZwweMDjX-Yj5TRLbqJ9FebvJxEz919nK6iNSY3TQpLxXJ6FL29eBj39-BDwB3AM6CFiCAcxi57JQUDW-6mJd3Ntx6vLWwLaIphy1k3KtxaWNZx0Q25RCXSr-eZsP1S9RMU93bEQOdE0ZjV_RXXLoK-rqnc0cd8V1WJMJ8gZ8OFIxCDAOraj7VquK_0B9NFHk2" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
           Personality change associated with psychedelic (LSD) therapy
          </a>
         </em>
         at its 1964 meeting.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         But psychedelics jumped from the lab and into the counterculture. In 1960, Harvard clinical psychologist Timothy Leary started the
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUEGOwyAQe005RkBKGw4c9rLaY3-ABpimbAlEA2mV3y9tDyuNZI0ty7I9NJwL7WYttbGtItkYjDjJaVRHzYI5BjGpicVqr4S4QEym0YZs3VyKHlos-e3gXCp2M1qCVojd4oQM6PSIboTpdNIQrlx1X8-xsIWI2aPBB9JeMrJkbq2t9TB-HeR3P8zDM97jiiHCUGju1Ovv8AP0AAr2UmMqfncx2wuVX_SNRSO55EJwLUY1jXIQg8o0PwmEC3g48mWWQ91cbeDvgy8LI5NLc4Vinrt8v8GC6S30erbjsuXYdosZXMLwad4-W72LtH1Fk_FZE7aG9CFfc0xcS3k-s54WSl8t_wf9AU-pgL4" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          Harvard Psilocybin Project
         </a>
         with Richard Alpert (who would later become Ram Dass) using psilocybin they ordered from Sandoz. The Project undertook some legitimate research, like the Marsh Chapel Experiment in which divinity students were administered the drug in a chapel to determine whether it could facilitate profound religious states (ten out of ten self-reported that it did), but largely devolved into the epicenter of recreational psilocybin and LSD use.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Harvard shut down the project in 1962, but Leary continued his work spreading the word about mushrooms and LSD. In 1966, he famously told America\xe2\x80\x99s youth to \xe2\x80\x9cTurn on, tune in, drop out.\xe2\x80\x9d Despite pleading from serious researchers who feared that Leary was going to \xe2\x80\x9cwreak havoc on all of us doing LSD work all over the nation,\xe2\x80\x9d Leary pushed on, like the friend who gets too high and gets everyone in trouble. According to Pollan, Leary said things like \xe2\x80\x9cLSD is more frightening than the bomb,\xe2\x80\x9d and \xe2\x80\x9cThe kids who take LSD aren\xe2\x80\x99t going to fight your wars. They\xe2\x80\x99re not going to join your corporations.\xe2\x80\x9d
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The FDA didn\xe2\x80\x99t like the sound of that, ordering in 1966 that researchers halt all work with psychedelics. Neither did Tricky Dick. In 1970, in large part to slow down the anti-war counterculture movement, the Nixon government passed the Controlled Substances Act, which classified psilocybin and LSD as Schedule One drugs, which have no medical use and a high potential for abuse. In 1971 Richard Nixon declared the War on Drugs and labeled Leary \xe2\x80\x9cthe most dangerous man in America.\xe2\x80\x9d
        </p>
